		<div id="siteNotice"><script type='text/javascript'>if (wgNotice != '') document.writeln(wgNotice);</script></div>		<h1 id="firstHeading" class="firstHeading">Story within a story</h1>
		<div id="bodyContent">
			<h3 id="siteSub">From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia</h3>
			<div id="contentSub"></div>
									<div id="jump-to-nav">Jump to: <a href="#column-one">navigation</a>, <a href="#searchInput">search</a></div>			<!-- start content -->
			<p>A <b>story within a story</b> is a <a href="/wiki/Literary_device" title="Literary device" class="mw-redirect">literary device</a> or <a href="/wiki/Conceit" title="Conceit">conceit</a> in which one story is told during the action of another story. <i><b><a href="/wiki/Mise_en_abyme" title="Mise en abyme">Mise en abyme</a></b></i> is the <a href="/wiki/French_language" title="French language">French</a> term for a similar literary device (also referring to the practice in <a href="/wiki/Heraldry" title="Heraldry">heraldry</a> of placing the image of a small shield on a larger shield). A story within a story can be used in <a href="/wiki/Novel" title="Novel">novels</a>, <a href="/wiki/Short_stories" title="Short stories" class="mw-redirect">short stories</a>, <a href="/wiki/Play_(theatre)" title="Play (theatre)">plays</a>, <a href="/wiki/Television" title="Television">television</a>, <a href="/wiki/Film" title="Film">films</a>, <a href="/wiki/Poem" title="Poem" class="mw-redirect">poems</a>, <a href="/wiki/Music" title="Music">music</a>, and even <a href="/wiki/Philosophy" title="Philosophy">philosophy</a>. A 1903 work is entitled <i>A Story Within a Story</i> <a href="http://books.google.com/books?q=%22story+within+a+story%22&amp;btnG=Search+Books" class="external autonumber" title="http://books.google.com/books?q=%22story+within+a+story%22&amp;btnG=Search+Books" rel="nofollow">[1]</a></p>
<table id="toc" class="toc" summary="Contents">
<tr>
<td>
